<BaseLayout
  title="Mission Fellowships | US Fellows"
  description="Structured US Fellows appointments centered on defined public-interest missions."
  canonical="https://usfellows.org/mission-fellowships.html"
  activePage="fellowships"
>
  <main id="main"><header class="page-hero page-hero--centered"><div class="container"><div class="breadcrumbs"><a href="index.html">Home</a> / <a href="fellowships.html">Fellowships</a> / Mission Fellowships</div><span class="kicker">Mission fellowships</span><h1>Begin with the mission</h1><p>A Mission Fellowship is structured around a defined area of public consequence, a capable Fellow, a qualified host, and an accountable contribution.</p></div></header><section class="manifesto-opening" id="overview"><div class="container"><span class="eyebrow">The fellowship pathway</span><p class="manifesto-statement">Mission Fellowships are organized around a defined public-interest challenge rather than a conventional job category or a single professional discipline.</p><div class="manifesto-detail"><h2>Appointments that begin with a consequential need</h2><p>They are especially useful when the work requires cross-disciplinary thinking, a bounded project, or focused capacity inside a mission-driven institution.</p></div></div></section><section class="section" id="principles"><div class="container"><div class="section-intro"><span class="eyebrow">Appointment standard</span><h2>Commitments behind a credible fellowship</h2><div class="rule"></div><p>A strong appointment aligns the Fellow, the institution, and the public value of the work.</p></div><div class="principle-pillars"><article class="card card--numbered"><span class="card__number">01</span><h3>Field alignment</h3><p>A Fellow&#x27;s knowledge and capabilities should be relevant to the work the appointment requires. In this context, consider research and synthesis.</p></article><article class="card card--numbered"><span class="card__number">02</span><h3>Institutional fit</h3><p>The host setting should make the contribution feasible, responsible, and useful. In this context, consider civic and institutional innovation.</p></article><article class="card card--numbered"><span class="card__number">03</span><h3>Public value</h3><p>The appointment should create benefit beyond private career advancement or organizational convenience. In this context, consider advisory contribution.</p></article></div></div></section><section class="section section--blue" id="process"><div class="container process-split"><div><div class="section-intro"><span class="eyebrow">From intent to practice</span><h2>From interest to appointment</h2><div class="rule"></div><p>Appointments are shaped deliberately so that recognition, institutional affiliation, and useful work reinforce one another.</p></div></div><div class="timeline"><article class="timeline-step"><span>01</span><div><h3>Express interest</h3><p>Describe your record, field, mission interests, and the contribution you are ready to make. Attend specifically to research and synthesis.</p></div></article><article class="timeline-step"><span>02</span><div><h3>Establish fit</h3><p>Consider merit, readiness, mission alignment, and the setting in which the work can succeed. Attend specifically to civic and institutional innovation.</p></div></article><article class="timeline-step"><span>03</span><div><h3>Define the appointment</h3><p>Confirm scope, host support, responsibilities, intended benefit, and a practical working cadence. Attend specifically to advisory contribution.</p></div></article><article class="timeline-step"><span>04</span><div><h3>Serve and reflect</h3><p>Complete the work with rigor, participate in Society life, and share transferable learning. Attend specifically to field-based service.</p></div></article></div></div></section><section class="narrative-focus" id="focus"><div class="container"><span class="eyebrow">The story of the work</span><h2>Four chapters of contribution</h2><article class="focus-item"><LegacyIcon name="compass" /><div><span class="item-index">01</span><h3>Research and synthesis</h3><p>Clarify a question, gather evidence, map a field, or translate knowledge for institutional use.</p></div></article><article class="focus-item"><LegacyIcon name="institution" /><div><span class="item-index">02</span><h3>Civic and institutional innovation</h3><p>Design or test practical improvements to access, services, operations, or public engagement.</p></div></article><article class="focus-item"><LegacyIcon name="lightbulb-o" /><div><span class="item-index">03</span><h3>Advisory contribution</h3><p>Bring experienced judgment to strategy, governance, technical questions, or mission development.</p></div></article><article class="focus-item"><LegacyIcon name="handshake-o" /><div><span class="item-index">04</span><h3>Field-based service</h3><p>Support implementation, partnership, education, documentation, or learning close to the work itself.</p></div></article></div></section><section class="close-banner" id="next"><div class="container"><div><h2>Move from interest toward appointment</h2><p>Begin with research and synthesis, then define a contribution your capabilities or institution can support.</p></div><div class="actions"><a class="button button--gold" href="apply.html">Become a Fellow</a><a class="button button--outline" href="fellowship-programs.html">View programs</a></div></div></section><div class="container close-related"><aside class="related-panel"><span class="eyebrow">Continue exploring</span><h3>Related pathways</h3><ul class="related-list"><li><a href="fellowship-programs.html">Fellowship programs</a></li><li><a href="selection-criteria.html">Selection criteria</a></li><li><a href="fellow-benefits.html">The Fellow experience</a></li></ul></aside></div></main>

</BaseLayout>
